{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17606861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17606861"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:17:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:17:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15933"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15933"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.29,0.25,0.04,0.43]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8624"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63238"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8624"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15933"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48689"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8457"},{"type":"tags","id":"8639"},{"type":"tags","id":"8644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20654"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20655"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63238"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ELung development occurs in distinct stages, with specific structural and functional changes occurring at each phase. The ability for extrauterine survival without surfactant replacement therapy depends on adequate maturation of type II pneumocytes and sufficient endogenous surfactant production.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following stages of lung development represents the earliest point at which survival without exogenous surfactant replacement becomes possible?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Embryonic stage","Saccular stage","Canalicular stage","Pseudoglandular stage","Alveolar stage"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esaccular stage\u003C/strong\u003E of respiratory development represents the earliest point at which endogenous surfactant production becomes sufficient for unassisted breathing. Key stages of lung development are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eembryonic stage\u003C/strong\u003E (3-7 weeks) involves formation of the lung buds and major airways\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epseudoglandular stage\u003C/strong\u003E (7-16 weeks) sees development of conducting airways and bronchial tree\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecanalicular stage\u003C/strong\u003E (16-26 weeks) marks the beginning of surfactant production, but quantities are insufficient for independent breathing\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esaccular stage\u003C/strong\u003E (26-36 weeks) represents when type II pneumocytes mature sufficiently to produce adequate surfactant for independent respiratory function\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ealveolar stage\u003C/strong\u003E (36 weeks to 8 years) represents full maturation with development of true alveoli\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile survival is possible from 24 weeks with intensive care and exogenous surfactant replacement, endogenous surfactant production typically becomes sufficient around 26 weeks as the saccular stage begins.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The saccular stage (26-36 weeks) marks when endogenous surfactant production becomes sufficient for unassisted breathing.","Before 26 weeks gestation, exogenous surfactant replacement is typically required for survival.","Type II pneumocytes must mature sufficiently to produce adequate surfactant for independent respiratory function."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015.","Koh TH, Harrison H, Casey A. Prediction of survival for preterm births. Survival table was not easy to understand. BMJ. 2000 Mar 4;320(7235):647.","Draper ES, Manktelow B, Field DJ, James D. Prediction of survival for preterm births by weight and gestational age: retrospective population based study. BMJ. 1999 Oct 23;319(7217):1093-7.","Erika M. Edwards, Danielle E. Y. Ehret, Roger F. Soll, Jeffrey D. Horbar; Survival of Infants Born at 22 to 25 Weeks\u2019 Gestation Receiving Care in the NICU: 2020\u20132022. Pediatrics October 2024; 154 (4): e2024065963."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48689"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15933"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48689"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T11:21:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T11:22:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8624"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63238"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medica